00:06:50.430 --> 00:06:51.810
TODD KERPELMAN: That is true.

00:06:51.810 --> 00:06:54.030
But you can't speed it up.

00:06:54.030 --> 00:06:56.260
Maybe if you send it
through a vacuum.

00:06:56.260 --> 00:06:59.470
But the problem is yeah, you can
get a whole bunch of data

00:06:59.470 --> 00:07:00.280
really fast.

00:07:00.280 --> 00:07:04.360
But if you need that less than
100 millisecond delay between

00:07:04.360 --> 00:07:07.215
when I press the fire button and
my character fires, how do

00:07:07.215 --> 00:07:08.330
you deal with that?

00:07:08.330 --> 00:07:10.575
JOHN MCCUTCHAN: I already get
much more lower ping times

00:07:10.575 --> 00:07:13.440
than 100 milliseconds today.

00:07:13.440 --> 00:07:15.900
I get ping times of 10
milliseconds, easily.

00:07:15.900 --> 00:07:17.820
DAN GALPIN: Yeah.

00:07:17.820 --> 00:07:19.380
To be honest, I think it's
somewhere in between.

00:07:19.380 --> 00:07:21.210
I really think that the
concept of installing

00:07:21.210 --> 00:07:22.480
software goes away.

00:07:22.480 --> 00:07:24.680
Whether that software is
physically running on your

00:07:24.680 --> 00:07:27.450
machine, or whether it's
actually running on some Cloud

00:07:27.450 --> 00:07:29.675
system is really going to depend
on what makes sense for

00:07:29.675 --> 00:07:30.580
that piece of software.

00:07:30.580 --> 00:07:32.790
But I think there's a lot of
things that are going to be

00:07:32.790 --> 00:07:34.720
able to run in the browser just
because you're not going

00:07:34.720 --> 00:07:37.330
to have to worry about
actually going off--

00:07:37.330 --> 00:07:38.802
it's not going to be slow,
particularly, to

00:07:38.802 --> 00:07:39.800
go and fetch textures.

00:07:39.800 --> 00:07:41.900
And all you're going to have
is a cache, basically, for

00:07:41.900 --> 00:07:43.540
anything you're running.

00:07:43.540 --> 00:07:45.230
So I think for distribution
it does eliminate that.

