00:18:53.790 --> 00:18:55.920
know who to root for-- it's
a group of three guys.

00:18:55.920 --> 00:18:58.130
It's along with making
connections with the players,

00:18:58.130 --> 00:19:00.890
but I also think these guys need
to just start creating

00:19:00.890 --> 00:19:02.070
regional affiliations.

00:19:02.070 --> 00:19:02.650
JOHN MCCUTCHAN: Totally.

00:19:02.650 --> 00:19:04.620
TODD KERPELMAN: I can go
to any baseball game--

00:19:04.620 --> 00:19:06.300
if I didn't know baseball, I
could still go to a baseball

00:19:06.300 --> 00:19:08.420
game and know, well, I'm going
to root for the team that

00:19:08.420 --> 00:19:09.630
represents my city.

00:19:09.630 --> 00:19:11.780
Like, you can just do that.

00:19:11.780 --> 00:19:13.280
DAN GALPIN: Like, you're going
to wear an orange panda hat.

00:19:13.280 --> 00:19:15.150
TODD KERPELMAN: I'm going to
wear an orange panda hat, and

00:19:15.150 --> 00:19:16.140
look ridiculous.

00:19:16.140 --> 00:19:18.430
And it's going to be OK,
because I'm from San

00:19:18.430 --> 00:19:20.340
Francisco, and that's
the team I know I am

00:19:20.340 --> 00:19:21.200
supposed to root for.

00:19:21.200 --> 00:19:25.260
I feel like there's nothing
right now that connects me to

00:19:25.260 --> 00:19:27.510
a particular "League of Legends"
team, unless, you

00:19:27.510 --> 00:19:29.530
know, maybe it's the world
championships, and there

00:19:29.530 --> 00:19:30.470
representing America.

00:19:30.470 --> 00:19:31.440
DAN GALPIN: That's right.

00:19:31.440 --> 00:19:32.410
JOHN MCCUTCHAN: I
agree with you.

00:19:32.410 --> 00:19:34.670
WOLFF DOBSON: Well, I do think
this comes to avatar

00:19:34.670 --> 00:19:36.890
customization, too, which is
like if people are carrying

00:19:36.890 --> 00:19:40.570
banners behind them, that really
tell these guys are on

00:19:40.570 --> 00:19:43.120
your side, and these guys are on
the other side, I think all

00:19:43.120 --> 00:19:45.610
of this stuff is about
signalling to the player

00:19:45.610 --> 00:19:46.770
what's going on.

00:19:46.770 --> 00:19:48.890
And anytime you're dealing with
cameras, anytime you're

00:19:48.890 --> 00:19:53.330
dealing with spectators,
what's going on is

00:19:53.330 --> 00:19:56.010
really hard to tell.

00:19:56.010 --> 00:19:59.190
Only games that are analogs of
actual sports have already

00:19:59.190 --> 00:20:00.080
figured that out.

00:20:00.080 --> 00:20:02.260
Basketball games and football
games really have

00:20:02.260 --> 00:20:03.570
that figured out.

00:20:03.570 --> 00:20:04.330
Can you imagine--

00:20:04.330 --> 00:20:07.070
it would be really cool to
watch a spectator game of

00:20:07.070 --> 00:20:09.820
"Splintercell," maybe.

00:20:09.820 --> 00:20:11.010
Or maybe it would
just be a lot of

00:20:11.010 --> 00:20:11.560
watching people not moving.

00:20:11.560 --> 00:20:12.757
TODD KERPELMAN: A lot of people
watching people wait.

00:20:12.757 --> 00:20:13.980
WOLFF DOBSON: Yes, exactly.

00:20:13.980 --> 00:20:14.960
TODD KERPELMAN: All right,
let's move on.

00:20:14.960 --> 00:20:16.600
WOLFF DOBSON: Sorry, it's
fun talking about that.

00:20:16.600 --> 00:20:17.370
DAN GALPIN: Speaking
of length--

00:20:17.370 --> 00:20:19.760
TODD KERPELMAN: Yes,
we were kind of--

00:20:19.760 --> 00:20:21.990
so this was a question
that Colt proposed.

00:20:21.990 --> 00:20:23.560
WOLFF DOBSON: Ah, yes,
that question.

00:20:23.560 --> 00:20:25.420
TODD KERPELMAN: And he proposed
the question, and

00:20:25.420 --> 00:20:28.280
then he didn't show
up for this.

00:20:28.280 --> 00:20:29.910
WOLFF DOBSON: At last
minute, I might add.

00:20:29.910 --> 00:20:31.540
TODD KERPELMAN: Yeah, so--

00:20:31.540 --> 00:20:32.355
DAN GALPIN: The audacity
of that person--

00:20:32.355 --> 00:20:33.715
WOLFF DOBSON: The Udac-- zing!

00:20:37.310 --> 00:20:39.820
TODD KERPELMAN: So, the question
he was asking is, in

00:20:39.820 --> 00:20:42.570
the modern gaming era, when
is a game too long?

00:20:42.570 --> 00:20:45.410
I think the point he's trying
to make is maybe now that

00:20:45.410 --> 00:20:48.370
we're all kind of playing on
phones and tablets and that

00:20:48.370 --> 00:20:50.970
sort of thing, gaming sessions
should be shorter.

00:20:50.970 --> 00:20:53.070
Or that would be
the more ideal.

00:20:53.070 --> 00:20:56.900
And I guess because John is
adjusting his mic, we'll start

00:20:56.900 --> 00:20:57.515
again with--

00:20:57.515 --> 00:21:00.960
JOHN MCCUTCHAN: All right,
hey, here we go.

00:21:00.960 --> 00:21:02.340
It's not the length of the
game that matters.

00:21:02.340 --> 00:21:06.120
It's how long it takes you
to get in and out.

00:21:06.120 --> 00:21:08.670
I would love to play a very
long game that takes--

00:21:08.670 --> 00:21:09.500
WOLFF DOBSON: Sorry.

00:21:09.500 --> 00:21:11.620
JOHN MCCUTCHAN: --that I could
play on my phone, but if it

00:21:11.620 --> 00:21:14.466
takes a minute to launch
the game--

00:21:14.466 --> 00:21:15.810
that in something like a
10 minute time window

00:21:15.810 --> 00:21:16.010
of playing the game--

00:21:16.010 --> 00:21:17.920
WOLFF DOBSON: Well, I think
this is a huge deal with

00:21:17.920 --> 00:21:19.680
mobile gaming.

00:21:19.680 --> 00:21:21.960
I always thought this was an
incredible weakness of the

00:21:21.960 --> 00:21:25.110
PSP, was waiting for that
disc to spin up.

00:21:25.110 --> 00:21:27.560
The joke was always that my DS
is a great thing to do while

00:21:27.560 --> 00:21:29.690
I'm waiting for my
PSP to boot.

00:21:29.690 --> 00:21:31.055
TODD KERPELMAN: I've never
heard that joke.

00:21:31.055 --> 00:21:31.965
That's funny.

00:21:31.965 --> 00:21:32.840
DAN GALPIN: Yeah, it's true.

00:21:32.840 --> 00:21:34.185
WOLFF DOBSON: It was
true for me, too.

00:21:34.185 --> 00:21:35.410
TODD KERPELMAN: But we
still like you, Sony.

00:21:35.410 --> 00:21:37.840
WOLFF DOBSON: I love you.

00:21:37.840 --> 00:21:38.760
JOHN MCCUTCHAN: You know,
I've been playing

00:21:38.760 --> 00:21:40.290
"X-Com" a lot lately.

00:21:40.290 --> 00:21:42.300
And sometimes I have 30 minutes
to play this game.

00:21:42.300 --> 00:21:45.080
And that's enough to play
a short mission.

00:21:45.080 --> 00:21:48.070
But five minutes of that is
spent booting into the game.

00:21:48.070 --> 00:21:52.730
It's turning the PS3 on and then
seeing all of the logos

00:21:52.730 --> 00:21:53.740
for all of the middleware.

00:21:53.740 --> 00:21:54.507
WOLFF DOBSON: I was going to
say, you know what we need?

00:21:54.507 --> 00:21:57.090
More animated logos
at the beginning.

00:21:57.090 --> 00:21:58.890
Especially games that are
licensed, so you have to have

00:21:58.890 --> 00:22:01.600
like three licensees, and then
the-- ah, it's awesome.

00:22:01.600 --> 00:22:01.870
I love that.

00:22:01.870 --> 00:22:04.030
DAN GALPIN: One of my greatest
pet peeves are people who do

00:22:04.030 --> 00:22:07.100
mobile games, and the mobile
game insists on playing at

00:22:07.100 --> 00:22:08.450
least two or three videos.

00:22:08.450 --> 00:22:11.030
And in some gaming worlds, they
might actually be doing

00:22:11.030 --> 00:22:13.080
something, like loading things
during the videos.

00:22:13.080 --> 00:22:16.480
But invariably, they're doing
nothing while those videos are

00:22:16.480 --> 00:22:18.630
playing, and the user is just
saying, I just want to get

00:22:18.630 --> 00:22:21.233
into the game, so I can have my
five minutes of gameplay.

00:22:21.233 --> 00:22:23.240
JOHN MCCUTCHAN: Yeah, show me as
many of your animated logos

00:22:23.240 --> 00:22:26.610
as you want, so long as you're
actually loading my saved game

00:22:26.610 --> 00:22:28.330
while you're doing it.

00:22:28.330 --> 00:22:29.850
DAN GALPIN: And the worst
thing-- and the other thing is

00:22:29.850 --> 00:22:32.110
that, in terms of mobile gaming,
you just want to be

00:22:32.110 --> 00:22:35.740
exactly where you left off
as quickly as possible.

00:22:35.740 --> 00:22:39.215
WOLFF DOBSON: Colt says games
should be links, links.

00:22:39.215 --> 00:22:42.390
JOHN MCCUTCHAN: I like this
cartoonization of Colt.

00:22:42.390 --> 00:22:44.690
WOLFF DOBSON: It's very easy.

00:22:44.690 --> 00:22:46.010
TODD KERPELMAN: i feel like
the puppet's had more

00:22:46.010 --> 00:22:47.550
insightful comments
so far then--

00:22:47.550 --> 00:22:48.583
DAN GALPIN: I was going
to say, Colt, what

00:22:48.583 --> 00:22:48.960
big glasses you have.

00:22:48.960 --> 00:22:49.890
TODD KERPELMAN: You're
invited back.

00:22:49.890 --> 00:22:50.630
WOLFF DOBSON: Oh boy,
oh boy, oh boy.

00:22:50.630 --> 00:22:52.620
DAN GALPIN: OK, so
where was I?

00:22:52.620 --> 00:22:55.460
So to me, I like the genius of
something like "Angry Birds."

00:22:55.460 --> 00:22:57.910
And I went back and
took a long look.

00:22:57.910 --> 00:23:00.720
Why was this game such a crazy,
breakout success?

00:23:00.720 --> 00:23:02.550
I had played games with
almost the exact

00:23:02.550 --> 00:23:04.120
same gameplay before.

00:23:04.120 --> 00:23:07.790
But it was you get in fast,
you get out fast.

00:23:07.790 --> 00:23:08.830
The levels--

00:23:08.830 --> 00:23:11.250
you feel a sense of
accomplishment quickly.

00:23:11.250 --> 00:23:14.410
Like a level in "Angry Birds," a
lot of them take 30 seconds,

00:23:14.410 --> 00:23:15.370
a minute to complete.

00:23:15.370 --> 00:23:16.770
Boom, I've accomplished
something.

00:23:16.770 --> 00:23:18.640
I've made some progression.

00:23:18.640 --> 00:23:22.320
But yet, to actually get through
the entire thing is a

00:23:22.320 --> 00:23:23.700
long slog of an experience.

00:23:23.700 --> 00:23:24.610
WOLFF DOBSON: Oh, it's
a relationship.

00:23:24.610 --> 00:23:27.740
And there's good data that the
longer people interact with

00:23:27.740 --> 00:23:28.450
your game--

00:23:28.450 --> 00:23:31.740
I mean, it's sort of obvious,
but you can actually see it.

00:23:31.740 --> 00:23:33.640
The longer people interact with
your game, the more they

00:23:33.640 --> 00:23:35.210
talk about it, the more they
share it with their friends,

00:23:35.210 --> 00:23:39.450
the bigger the viral hit of
your game is going to be.

00:23:39.450 --> 00:23:43.500
This is why "Dark Souls"
takes a long time

00:23:43.500 --> 00:23:44.450
to get through that.

00:23:44.450 --> 00:23:46.270
Games that you fire and forget,
and you're over with

00:23:46.270 --> 00:23:48.730
in three minutes make a
big splash for a week.

00:23:48.730 --> 00:23:50.560
And then everyone's playing
them, and it's over.

00:23:50.560 --> 00:23:51.430
JOHN MCCUTCHAN: Yeah, it's
a slow burn of a game.

00:23:51.430 --> 00:23:54.740
TODD KERPELMAN: So Daniel, as
our Android expert, do you

00:23:54.740 --> 00:23:58.000
actually have data on the
average play session time that

00:23:58.000 --> 00:24:00.852
people typically spend
with games?

00:24:00.852 --> 00:24:02.590
DAN GALPIN: It's funny
that you--

00:24:02.590 --> 00:24:03.120
we don't.

00:24:03.120 --> 00:24:07.620
And that's partially because
on Android we don't

00:24:07.620 --> 00:24:09.120
track what people do.

00:24:09.120 --> 00:24:10.320
That's just that simple.

00:24:10.320 --> 00:24:13.420
We don't have any hooks in to
see what people are doing.

00:24:13.420 --> 00:24:14.620
I'd love to know that, though.

00:24:14.620 --> 00:24:16.110
TODD KERPELMAN: Could you guys
email us and just let us know

00:24:16.110 --> 00:24:16.380
constantly?

00:24:16.380 --> 00:24:17.530
JOHN MCCUTCHAN: We
don't spy on you.

00:24:17.530 --> 00:24:18.400
DAN GALPIN: If some
developer wants to

00:24:18.400 --> 00:24:19.200
tell me, that's great.

00:24:19.200 --> 00:24:22.450
But we actually don't track any
usage on Android, so we

00:24:22.450 --> 00:24:24.150
don't really know.

00:24:24.150 --> 00:24:26.910
We only know when someone
installs something and when

00:24:26.910 --> 00:24:28.455
someone uninstalls something,
essentially.

00:24:28.455 --> 00:24:32.830
WOLFF DOBSON: I mean, the game
developers themselves are

00:24:32.830 --> 00:24:34.850
annotating the game with
analytics all over the place,

00:24:34.850 --> 00:24:35.320
you'd hope.

00:24:35.320 --> 00:24:37.200
And If you aren't,
please do so.

00:24:37.200 --> 00:24:37.920
DAN GALPIN: Absolutely.

00:24:37.920 --> 00:24:39.110
Help us.

00:24:39.110 --> 00:24:40.860
TODD KERPELMAN: And if you
are a game developer, put

00:24:40.860 --> 00:24:43.200
something in the comments right
now, and maybe Lewis

00:24:43.200 --> 00:24:43.860
will tell us.

00:24:43.860 --> 00:24:46.590
DAN GALPIN: And from what
I gather from the game

00:24:46.590 --> 00:24:48.010
companies, though, it really
depends on the game.

00:24:48.010 --> 00:24:51.090
There are games that appeal to
a really hardcore gamer.

00:24:51.090 --> 00:24:52.440
The sessions are longer.

00:24:52.440 --> 00:24:54.490
By definition they're longer,
especially since a lot of them

00:24:54.490 --> 00:24:56.420
don't have a good way of pausing
in the middle of the

00:24:56.420 --> 00:24:57.730
action, necessarily.

00:24:57.730 --> 00:25:01.400
So obviously those game times
are going to be very long.

00:25:01.400 --> 00:25:02.950
Something like "Angry Birds,"
it's very short.

00:25:02.950 --> 00:25:05.870
I think that Rovio has actually
released data about

00:25:05.870 --> 00:25:07.800
how long the average "Angry
Birds" session is.

00:25:07.800 --> 00:25:11.260
And actually, it was longer
than I expected.

00:25:11.260 --> 00:25:14.160
But I think that's simply
because the game is so

00:25:14.160 --> 00:25:17.560
ridiculously addictive.

00:25:17.560 --> 00:25:19.950
But yeah, I think there's no
limit to the length of a game.

00:25:19.950 --> 00:25:21.480
In fact, what we've seen is that
the games that are most

00:25:21.480 --> 00:25:23.680
successful are the games that
build a franchise, the games

00:25:23.680 --> 00:25:26.870
that continue to add and
add and add content.

00:25:26.870 --> 00:25:29.550
As long as the content has value
and the consumer feels

00:25:29.550 --> 00:25:32.010
like they're not just rolling
through the same mechanics

00:25:32.010 --> 00:25:36.190
over and over and over again,
they'll play out a long way in

00:25:36.190 --> 00:25:37.000
terms of content.

00:25:37.000 --> 00:25:39.380
So I don't think there's any
such thing as a game that's

00:25:39.380 --> 00:25:41.630
too long, certainly.

00:25:41.630 --> 00:25:44.510
There is a game that's too large
in terms of how much

00:25:44.510 --> 00:25:45.890
space it takes up
on the device.

00:25:45.890 --> 00:25:47.740
WOLFF DOBSON: There are games
that are too long, though.

00:25:47.740 --> 00:25:49.580
There are definitely games that
overstay their welcome,

00:25:49.580 --> 00:25:53.910
but that's much more about the
artistic side, where it's

00:25:53.910 --> 00:25:56.590
like, you know I haven't done
anything new in a while.

00:25:56.590 --> 00:25:57.825
This plot went off the rails.

00:25:57.825 --> 00:25:59.370
TODD KERPELMAN: This level
feels like padding.

00:25:59.370 --> 00:26:00.760
JOHN MCCUTCHAN: I think Dan
was getting at that.

00:26:00.760 --> 00:26:01.770
Oftentimes I'll play game.

00:26:01.770 --> 00:26:04.190
And the first half an
hour, I'm loving it.

00:26:04.190 --> 00:26:06.840
And then I'm like, hey, you know
what, this half hour just

00:26:06.840 --> 00:26:08.740
feels like I'm doing the
same thing again

00:26:08.740 --> 00:26:11.080
and again and again.

00:26:11.080 --> 00:26:13.075
TODD KERPELMAN: We're going to
move on, but we do have a-- is

00:26:13.075 --> 00:26:13.480
there a question?

00:26:13.480 --> 00:26:14.473
AUDIENCE: Yeah, you guys were
talking about platforms and

00:26:14.473 --> 00:26:16.210
you brought up PSP and all
these different things.

00:26:16.210 --> 00:26:17.130
WOLFF DOBSON: Chrome.

00:26:17.130 --> 00:26:19.250
AUDIENCE: And there's the new
Wii U. We haven't talked about

00:26:19.250 --> 00:26:19.845
the Wii U, yet.

00:26:19.845 --> 00:26:20.550
WOLFF DOBSON: Oh, yeah.

00:26:20.550 --> 00:26:23.270
AUDIENCE: So, Pedro was asking,
do you find that

00:26:23.270 --> 00:26:26.620
today's platforms, Xbox, PSP,
all of the ones that are out

00:26:26.620 --> 00:26:29.450
there-- are they sufficient
for today's market?

00:26:29.450 --> 00:26:31.560
Will the Wii U do something
brand new?

00:26:31.560 --> 00:26:32.240
And what's missing?

00:26:32.240 --> 00:26:34.780
I just want to get your take on
the console market today.

00:26:34.780 --> 00:26:36.565
TODD KERPELMAN: Good
question, Pedro.

00:26:36.565 --> 00:26:37.610
JOHN MCCUTCHAN: All
right, Pedro.

00:26:37.610 --> 00:26:39.550
So I have a Wii U, and--

00:26:39.550 --> 00:26:41.660
WOLFF DOBSON: Oh,
wow, how is it?

00:26:41.660 --> 00:26:44.180
JOHN MCCUTCHAN: It's great.

00:26:44.180 --> 00:26:46.440
I have "Nintendo Land" and
"Mario." And so "Mario,"

00:26:46.440 --> 00:26:48.250
everyone knows what you're
getting when you buy "Mario."

00:26:48.250 --> 00:26:50.360
But "Nintendo Land" actually
has some really interesting

00:26:50.360 --> 00:26:51.760
gameplay ideas.

00:26:51.760 --> 00:26:55.390
And I would consider that it's
not technically new in that

00:26:55.390 --> 00:26:57.810
it's groundbreaking, but it's
never been attempted to be

00:26:57.810 --> 00:27:02.080
done on this scale and to this
mainstream audience, which is

00:27:02.080 --> 00:27:03.730
asymmetrical gaming.

00:27:03.730 --> 00:27:06.760
One of the games that we keep
playing over and over and over

00:27:06.760 --> 00:27:09.300
again is "Luigi's Mansion,"
or something like that.

00:27:09.300 --> 00:27:13.410
And it's not the old "Luigi's
Mansion." It's essentially a

00:27:13.410 --> 00:27:18.820
mini game where the player with
the tablet is a ghost and

00:27:18.820 --> 00:27:21.650
is trying to take down everyone

00:27:21.650 --> 00:27:22.830
who's looking for them.

00:27:22.830 --> 00:27:25.830
The other players are using the
old Wii-mote controllers.

00:27:25.830 --> 00:27:26.530
DAN GALPIN: So it's
"Splinter Cell."

00:27:26.530 --> 00:27:28.270
JOHN MCCUTCHAN: I don't know.

00:27:28.270 --> 00:27:29.100
Not exactly.

00:27:29.100 --> 00:27:30.665
WOLFF DOBSON: Mario
"Splinter Cell."

00:27:30.665 --> 00:27:32.560
JOHN MCCUTCHAN: So the other
players have the flashlight,

00:27:32.560 --> 00:27:35.170
and if they point it at the
ghost, which they can't see on

00:27:35.170 --> 00:27:37.980
the television, the ghost lights
up and takes damage.

00:27:37.980 --> 00:27:39.720
And then when the ghost
gets down to zero

00:27:39.720 --> 00:27:40.910
health, game over.

00:27:40.910 --> 00:27:42.043
WOLFF DOBSON: But the flashlight
has some timer on

00:27:42.043 --> 00:27:42.560
it, or something.

00:27:42.560 --> 00:27:45.240
JOHN MCCUTCHAN: The flashlight
has batteries which will

00:27:45.240 --> 00:27:46.250
appear randomly.

00:27:46.250 --> 00:27:48.530
But that's a great trap
for the ghost.

00:27:48.530 --> 00:27:49.990
WOLFF DOBSON: They're like
"X-Files" flashlights that are

00:27:49.990 --> 00:27:53.100
only this wide, no matter how
dangerous the thing is.

00:27:53.100 --> 00:27:53.670
JOHN MCCUTCHAN: Yes, yes.

00:27:53.670 --> 00:27:53.985
It doesn't matter.

00:27:53.985 --> 00:27:55.590
It's very targeted.

00:27:55.590 --> 00:28:00.340
But that game is ridiculously
fun because of the extra

00:28:00.340 --> 00:28:03.440
information that the ghost
player has, which is you can

00:28:03.440 --> 00:28:04.170
see everything.

00:28:04.170 --> 00:28:07.490
You can see where every player
is, what's going on, do they

00:28:07.490 --> 00:28:09.800
need batteries, where the
battery is going to be.

00:28:09.800 --> 00:28:12.670
And so you can be kind of
lurking around a corner.

00:28:12.670 --> 00:28:14.480
And they're flashing around
and shaking everywhere.

00:28:14.480 --> 00:28:16.760
It's like, they go for the
battery, you take them down.

00:28:16.760 --> 00:28:20.346
WOLFF DOBSON: You're
like, I like games

00:28:20.346 --> 00:28:21.800
where I get to lurk.

00:28:21.800 --> 00:28:22.620
Lurking is good.

00:28:22.620 --> 00:28:24.790
JOHN MCCUTCHAN: And then the
other players try and

00:28:24.790 --> 00:28:26.470
resuscitate them, so it's
this weird dynamic.

00:28:26.470 --> 00:28:29.370
WOLFF DOBSON: I like games where
there's a ditch, where

00:28:29.370 --> 00:28:31.780
my friends are trying to pull
themselves back to life.

00:28:31.780 --> 00:28:36.870
JOHN MCCUTCHAN: It's this week
dynamic where whoever is the

00:28:36.870 --> 00:28:39.890
most powerful in the game is
always going back and forth.

00:28:39.890 --> 00:28:42.620
And it's all built around this
idea that one person who's

00:28:42.620 --> 00:28:45.460
playing the game has extra
information, extra knowledge

00:28:45.460 --> 00:28:49.445
which gives them an edge, but
still the game is balanced.

00:28:49.445 --> 00:28:50.700
WOLFF DOBSON: I've seen--

00:28:50.700 --> 00:28:55.950
there have been like source
engine mods that had games

00:28:55.950 --> 00:28:58.470
like that, where one guy can
run up walls and everybody

00:28:58.470 --> 00:29:00.520
else can't, and things
like that.

00:29:00.520 --> 00:29:05.270
I think that kind of game
is pretty cool.

00:29:05.270 --> 00:29:08.210
DAN GALPIN: I think the great
thing about that kind of

00:29:08.210 --> 00:29:11.010
device is really just the
ability to do a lot of things.

00:29:11.010 --> 00:29:14.150
You can do a lot of the same
thing with any computer and

00:29:14.150 --> 00:29:16.750
any kind of second screen
device, whether that's an

00:29:16.750 --> 00:29:20.410
Android device or a Chromebook,
or whatever you

00:29:20.410 --> 00:29:21.060
might have.

00:29:21.060 --> 00:29:24.610
But what's great about that
is that it makes it

00:29:24.610 --> 00:29:26.030
absolutely real time.

00:29:26.030 --> 00:29:29.620
I mean the technology there is
that your display is coming

00:29:29.620 --> 00:29:35.460
off of the Wii U, and so it is
as fast as it can transmit the

00:29:35.460 --> 00:29:36.470
bits over the air.

00:29:36.470 --> 00:29:39.930
And that, to me, is really the
only difference between that

00:29:39.930 --> 00:29:42.170
and actually just having a
tablet sitting next to your

00:29:42.170 --> 00:29:44.420
console, is just how real
time you can do it.

00:29:44.420 --> 00:29:45.750
WOLFF DOBSON: So this goes
back to our latency

00:29:45.750 --> 00:29:47.305
conversation.

00:29:47.305 --> 00:29:51.650
JOHN MCCUTCHAN: It's not only
latency, because it's keeping

00:29:51.650 --> 00:29:52.810
the two in sync.

00:29:52.810 --> 00:29:55.370
Like, hey, I've got a tablet,
and I can have a second screen

00:29:55.370 --> 00:29:58.430
experience, but how do they
synchronize with each other?

00:29:58.430 --> 00:30:00.730
How does the game actually
initiate where-- since it's

00:30:00.730 --> 00:30:03.020
all running on the Wii U,
they're just in sync

00:30:03.020 --> 00:30:03.580
automatically.

00:30:03.580 --> 00:30:05.770
DAN GALPIN: One of the things
that I'm really excited about

00:30:05.770 --> 00:30:09.200
with the latest version of
Android is we actually finally

00:30:09.200 --> 00:30:11.170
enabled something that I've
wanted for a long time, which

00:30:11.170 --> 00:30:12.670
is true multi display.

00:30:12.670 --> 00:30:18.470
So today, in theory, you could
actually hook up true multiple

00:30:18.470 --> 00:30:21.360
displays coming off of a
single Android device.

00:30:21.360 --> 00:30:22.930
WOLFF DOBSON: So are you
chaining it with cables?

00:30:22.930 --> 00:30:23.980
Or how does that work?

00:30:23.980 --> 00:30:28.700
DAN GALPIN: Well, on something
like the Nexus 4, you actually

00:30:28.700 --> 00:30:29.990
can do it over Mirror Cast.

00:30:29.990 --> 00:30:33.010
You can do it over
Wi-Fi Direct.

00:30:33.010 --> 00:30:36.190
And that display is completely
driven by that device.

00:30:36.190 --> 00:30:38.575
It's just a stream that
comes off of it.

00:30:38.575 --> 00:30:39.710
JOHN MCCUTCHAN: I think that's
how the Wii U operates.

00:30:39.710 --> 00:30:40.935
DAN GALPIN: That actually is.

00:30:40.935 --> 00:30:42.310
It's very similar.

00:30:42.310 --> 00:30:44.960
The only thing about the Wii U
is that they've customized it

00:30:44.960 --> 00:30:46.990
so that they have minimal
latency and all of that.

00:30:46.990 --> 00:30:48.720
JOHN MCCUTCHAN: Its crazy
how low latency is.

00:30:48.720 --> 00:30:52.170
I've held it and been watching
the game on the TV and on the

00:30:52.170 --> 00:30:53.985
tablet, and they're
just mirrored.

00:30:53.985 --> 00:30:55.390
It's imperceivable to me.

00:30:55.390 --> 00:30:57.330
WOLFF DOBSON: Going back
to latency-- oh sorry.

00:30:57.330 --> 00:31:00.560
TODD KERPELMAN: Going back, I
was going to tie it back to

00:31:00.560 --> 00:31:02.840
our original question of what
are consoles missing.

00:31:02.840 --> 00:31:04.980
That seems like a
nice feature.

00:31:04.980 --> 00:31:06.210
I don't know if that's the--

00:31:06.210 --> 00:31:09.160
WOLFF DOBSON: I will say on
the Dreamcast, we had the

00:31:09.160 --> 00:31:10.980
second screen right
there, my friend.

00:31:10.980 --> 00:31:14.030
DAN GALPIN: I remember back when
the Dreamcast was around.

00:31:14.030 --> 00:31:14.990
WOLFF DOBSON: Back in my day.

00:31:14.990 --> 00:31:18.800
JOHN MCCUTCHAN: It was 16
columns by 16 columns.

00:31:18.800 --> 00:31:20.280
DAN GALPIN: I was amazed at how
many different gameplay

00:31:20.280 --> 00:31:21.770
experiences that enabled,
though.

00:31:21.770 --> 00:31:25.610
Like, the little Dreamcast,
everything from little

00:31:25.610 --> 00:31:27.280
mini-games that you would
do on those things.

00:31:27.280 --> 00:31:28.980
Sometimes you would even take
it away from the console.

00:31:28.980 --> 00:31:29.900
WOLFF DOBSON: Oh, yeah.

00:31:29.900 --> 00:31:34.450
The little Chaos things from
"Sonic Adventure."

00:31:34.450 --> 00:31:35.900
TODD KERPELMAN: They were great,
except the battery

00:31:35.900 --> 00:31:37.260
lasted about, like--

00:31:37.260 --> 00:31:37.850
DAN GALPIN: Yeah.

00:31:37.850 --> 00:31:40.330
WOLFF DOBSON: That, and then
they added that huge noise

00:31:40.330 --> 00:31:43.940
whenever it turns on, saying
my battery is dead.

00:31:43.940 --> 00:31:46.490
And of course, I still
have my Dreamcast.

00:31:46.490 --> 00:31:49.260
You plug it in 12 years later,
and it's like, I don't even

00:31:49.260 --> 00:31:50.460
know if I can buy a
battery for this.

00:31:50.460 --> 00:31:54.320
And it's going, beep, save me.

00:31:54.320 --> 00:31:56.280
No, but it is interesting.

00:31:56.280 --> 00:31:56.960
And I think--

00:31:56.960 --> 00:32:00.090
I mean, going forward in time
a little bit, from when

00:32:00.090 --> 00:32:01.830
dinosaurs roamed the earth--

00:32:01.830 --> 00:32:05.900
there was also "Four Swords,"
"Zelda, Four Swords," where

00:32:05.900 --> 00:32:07.420
you plugged in.

00:32:07.420 --> 00:32:09.450
It was such an expensive
thing to set up.

00:32:09.450 --> 00:32:09.850
DAN GALPIN: Yes.

00:32:09.850 --> 00:32:13.720
WOLFF DOBSON: But when you
did, it was so cool.

00:32:13.720 --> 00:32:16.210
We played a ton of that,
where you have a

00:32:16.210 --> 00:32:17.980
GameCube and then four--

00:32:17.980 --> 00:32:19.030
TODD KERPELMAN: Four GBAs.

00:32:19.030 --> 00:32:20.540
WOLFF DOBSON: Yeah, Game Boy
Advances hooked up to it.

00:32:20.540 --> 00:32:23.620
And I think, actually, when you
think about where we came

00:32:23.620 --> 00:32:24.280
from, like--

00:32:24.280 --> 00:32:24.950
DAN GALPIN: Yes.

00:32:24.950 --> 00:32:26.730
WOLFF DOBSON: They have
absolutely been interested in

00:32:26.730 --> 00:32:27.890
this for a long time.

00:32:27.890 --> 00:32:29.680
TODD KERPELMAN: All right, I'm
going to stop us and move on

00:32:29.680 --> 00:32:33.090
to, I guess, what will be our
last question, which is--

00:32:33.090 --> 00:32:33.610
WOLFF DOBSON: Chrome.

00:32:33.610 --> 00:32:34.760
TODD KERPELMAN: Yeah.

00:32:34.760 --> 00:32:35.750
WOLFF DOBSON: Chrome
is the answer.

00:32:35.750 --> 00:32:36.740
TODD KERPELMAN: So
I'm pretty sure.

00:32:36.740 --> 00:32:38.510
Actually, Dan, I don't know if
you've actually worked in the

00:32:38.510 --> 00:32:38.890
games industry.

00:32:38.890 --> 00:32:39.090
DAN GALPIN: No.

00:32:39.090 --> 00:32:39.390
TODD KERPELMAN: No.

00:32:39.390 --> 00:32:40.050
DAN GALPIN: No.

00:32:40.050 --> 00:32:41.840
I have no good answer
to this question.

00:32:41.840 --> 00:32:42.200
TODD KERPELMAN: Wow.

00:32:42.200 --> 00:32:44.290
All right, so you're not
allowed to answer.

00:32:44.290 --> 00:32:47.380
WOLFF DOBSON: Ah, ah,
I worked for years.

00:32:47.380 --> 00:32:48.450
TODD KERPELMAN: I know everyone

00:32:48.450 --> 00:32:50.350
else, and Puppet Colt--

00:32:50.350 --> 00:32:50.740
WOLFF DOBSON: Yes.

00:32:50.740 --> 00:32:51.920
TODD KERPELMAN: --has worked
in the games industry.

00:32:51.920 --> 00:32:53.840
We might have people who
are the industry--

00:32:53.840 --> 00:32:56.160
WOLFF DOBSON: I worked
my paws to the bone.

00:32:56.160 --> 00:32:57.970
TODD KERPELMAN: But we might
also have people who are

00:32:57.970 --> 00:33:01.330
wondering, hey, how do I get
into the games industry?

00:33:01.330 --> 00:33:02.730
WOLFF DOBSON: I worked
on the "paws" menu.

00:33:02.730 --> 00:33:04.380
Ah.

00:33:04.380 --> 00:33:05.180
Oh, no.

00:33:05.180 --> 00:33:06.222
Ah.

00:33:06.222 --> 00:33:06.614
DAN GALPIN: Colt--

00:33:06.614 --> 00:33:07.400
WOLFF DOBSON: It
had to happen.

00:33:07.400 --> 00:33:08.880
DAN GALPIN: --what big
eyes you have.

00:33:08.880 --> 00:33:09.600
TODD KERPELMAN: That
was funny.

00:33:09.600 --> 00:33:11.550
DAN GALPIN: Sorry, go on.

00:33:11.550 --> 00:33:12.817
WOLFF DOBSON: Sorry.

00:33:12.817 --> 00:33:14.523
TODD KERPELMAN: That was
funny, the "paws" menu.

00:33:17.944 --> 00:33:19.830
All right, so how
did you get your

00:33:19.830 --> 00:33:20.690
jobs in the game industry?

00:33:20.690 --> 00:33:23.420
What advice do you have for
people today that are looking

00:33:23.420 --> 00:33:24.740
to get into the industry?

00:33:24.740 --> 00:33:27.260
WOLFF DOBSON: Well, I went about
it in, I think, the most

00:33:27.260 --> 00:33:31.340
difficult way possible, because
I got a PhD in AI and

00:33:31.340 --> 00:33:35.270
then worked on weird
post-doc stuff.

00:33:35.270 --> 00:33:37.700
And then I was like, you
know what, I'm tired

00:33:37.700 --> 00:33:38.730
of the public sector.

00:33:38.730 --> 00:33:39.990
Let's try the private sector.

00:33:39.990 --> 00:33:43.750
And I sent my resume in
to a recruiter that I

00:33:43.750 --> 00:33:46.120
found on the internet.

00:33:46.120 --> 00:33:48.610
I did it about as badly as
you could possibly do it.

00:33:48.610 --> 00:33:54.140
However, then working with the
recruiter, I think the main

00:33:54.140 --> 00:33:59.970
thing that especially AAA
developers are looking for are

00:33:59.970 --> 00:34:01.740
people who can code.

00:34:01.740 --> 00:34:04.000
I mean, if you want to be an
artist, there's a whole other

00:34:04.000 --> 00:34:04.600
conversation.

00:34:04.600 --> 00:34:07.770
And actually, we should put that
on our Five For Five at

00:34:07.770 --> 00:34:12.389
some point, too, paths in that
aren't just developer, like

00:34:12.389 --> 00:34:13.440
straight coder.

00:34:13.440 --> 00:34:16.389
But you need to be
able to code.

00:34:16.389 --> 00:34:17.500
You're going to be tested.

00:34:17.500 --> 00:34:18.949
You're going to be
given a test.

00:34:18.949 --> 00:34:20.880
You gotta know this stuff, just
because there's so many

00:34:20.880 --> 00:34:23.219
people who want to develop
games, because it's fun and

00:34:23.219 --> 00:34:26.489
it's neat, and it's got
a lot of glamour.

00:34:26.489 --> 00:34:29.900
Sort of.

00:34:29.900 --> 00:34:30.850
DAN GALPIN: Perceived glamour.

00:34:30.850 --> 00:34:32.360
WOLFF DOBSON: Yeah, exactly.

00:34:32.360 --> 00:34:34.114
TODD KERPELMAN: Remember all
those red carpet parties we

00:34:34.114 --> 00:34:34.960
used to go to?

00:34:34.960 --> 00:34:35.909
WOLFF DOBSON: Actually,
I went to one.

00:34:35.909 --> 00:34:37.489
I went to an actual
red carpet.

00:34:37.489 --> 00:34:38.630
TODD KERPELMAN: Really?

00:34:38.630 --> 00:34:40.670
WOLFF DOBSON: Yeah, when we
launched the Dreamcast-- once.

00:34:40.670 --> 00:34:41.139
JOHN MCCUTCHAN: E3 used
to be pretty--

00:34:41.139 --> 00:34:42.620
WOLFF DOBSON: Yeah, and
E3 is like fun.

00:34:42.620 --> 00:34:44.227
TODD KERPELMAN: All right,
all right, yeah.

00:34:44.227 --> 00:34:44.850
E3's--

00:34:44.850 --> 00:34:47.800
WOLFF DOBSON: But yeah, if you
want to go to parties, you

00:34:47.800 --> 00:34:48.969
should pick a different
industry.

00:34:48.969 --> 00:34:52.020
JOHN MCCUTCHAN: So totally to
your point, how I got into the

00:34:52.020 --> 00:34:56.070
games industry was, in grad
school I wrote a real-time 3D

00:34:56.070 --> 00:34:58.060
collision detection and physics
engine that was

00:34:58.060 --> 00:35:00.230
comparable to Bullet
and Havoc.

00:35:00.230 --> 00:35:03.120
And then Erwin Coumans hired me
to work at PlayStation to

00:35:03.120 --> 00:35:05.750
optimize Bullet for the PS3.

00:35:05.750 --> 00:35:06.480
And that was exactly it.

00:35:06.480 --> 00:35:11.880
Like, I just wrote an actual
physics engine from nuts to

00:35:11.880 --> 00:35:14.210
bolts, soups to nuts,
or whatever.

00:35:14.210 --> 00:35:15.310
WOLFF DOBSON: This
is a big deal.

00:35:15.310 --> 00:35:15.910
JOHN MCCUTCHAN: And
that was it.

00:35:15.910 --> 00:35:18.600
It was like, here's
my portfolio.

00:35:18.600 --> 00:35:20.880
It's a fully working engine.

00:35:20.880 --> 00:35:22.120
WOLFF DOBSON: And if you're
looking for engine work--

00:35:22.120 --> 00:35:23.230
I mean, you should build
the things that you

00:35:23.230 --> 00:35:23.850
want to work on.

00:35:23.850 --> 00:35:24.130
JOHN MCCUTCHAN: Yes.

00:35:24.130 --> 00:35:24.410
[INAUDIBLE].

00:35:24.410 --> 00:35:26.570
WOLFF DOBSON: Although I will
say, you may end up working on

00:35:26.570 --> 00:35:27.440
things that you didn't know--

00:35:27.440 --> 00:35:29.125
I mean, my first
job was sports.

00:35:29.125 --> 00:35:30.000
TODD KERPELMAN: You will
end up working on

00:35:30.000 --> 00:35:31.710
things almost certainly.

00:35:31.710 --> 00:35:33.250
JOHN MCCUTCHAN: Yeah, almost
certainly you're going to end

00:35:33.250 --> 00:35:34.920
up not really doing
what you want.

00:35:34.920 --> 00:35:36.425
But the advice that I give--

00:35:36.425 --> 00:35:38.130
WOLFF DOBSON: Welcome
to life, kids.

00:35:38.130 --> 00:35:39.330
You're not gonna do
what you want.

00:35:39.330 --> 00:35:41.995
JOHN MCCUTCHAN: Get ready
for disappointment.

00:35:41.995 --> 00:35:44.310
WOLFF DOBSON: Life from here
is nothing but pain.

00:35:44.310 --> 00:35:45.950
JOHN MCCUTCHAN: The advice I
give to everyone who asks this

00:35:45.950 --> 00:35:47.810
question is write the engine.

00:35:47.810 --> 00:35:49.630
Like, if you want
to be an engine

00:35:49.630 --> 00:35:52.060
engineer, write an engine.

00:35:52.060 --> 00:35:56.110
In your own time, by yourself,
do the hard work, and you'll

00:35:56.110 --> 00:35:57.845
get a job so easily.

00:35:57.845 --> 00:36:00.780
If you just show up with a
resume like, hey, I graduated

00:36:00.780 --> 00:36:02.610
with a computer science degree
and I want to write a game

00:36:02.610 --> 00:36:03.640
engine, good luck.

00:36:03.640 --> 00:36:05.910
WOLFF DOBSON: Well, the thing
is, in the game industry,

00:36:05.910 --> 00:36:06.990
you're looking for builders.

00:36:06.990 --> 00:36:10.770
You're looking for people who,
if you leave them alone in a

00:36:10.770 --> 00:36:14.790
room with a laptop, they will
start building a game.

00:36:14.790 --> 00:36:15.510
JOHN MCCUTCHAN: Exactly.

00:36:15.510 --> 00:36:19.700
WOLFF DOBSON: When I was
interviewing other developers,

00:36:19.700 --> 00:36:21.890
this is what I looked at,
like are you builder?

00:36:21.890 --> 00:36:23.200
Are you the kind
of person who--

00:36:23.200 --> 00:36:25.620
JOHN MCCUTCHAN: I would always
ask, what software have you

00:36:25.620 --> 00:36:26.750
written in your spare time?

00:36:26.750 --> 00:36:28.178
It's the biggest indicator.

00:36:28.178 --> 00:36:29.130
WOLFF DOBSON: Yeah.

00:36:29.130 --> 00:36:32.860
I mean, some people have got
really, really interesting and

00:36:32.860 --> 00:36:35.810
active outside-of-work lives,
which generally aren't game

00:36:35.810 --> 00:36:38.430
developers.

00:36:38.430 --> 00:36:41.130
But sometimes there's
some slack there.

00:36:41.130 --> 00:36:45.540
It's like, oh yeah, I do like
free climbing up Half Dome

00:36:45.540 --> 00:36:46.100
every weekend.

00:36:46.100 --> 00:36:47.500
It's like, OK, fine,
that's pretty cool.

00:36:47.500 --> 00:36:51.060
But otherwise it's like, yeah,
you should be building.

00:36:51.060 --> 00:36:54.810
You're not just like a huge
player, you're a builder.

00:36:54.810 --> 00:36:58.040
Gametribe games are a great
way to get into

00:36:58.040 --> 00:36:58.840
the groove of that.

